WQS Test of Selection – rrBlup Style

Timothy M. Beissinger

June 6, 2016

Data from Lorenz, 2015 (G3) will be re-visited to test the hypothesis that the reason selection mapping and GWAS yielded no results, despite moderate to high heritabilities and phenotypic change, was because the selected traits were highly quantitative. To do this, allelic effects will be estimated using GWAS and allele frequency change from cycle 2 to cycle 5 will be computed. Then, the sum of frequency change multiplied by effect size will be computed. If effects and frequency changes are related, this sum should be non-zero and in the direction that the trait was selected. A permutation test will be conducted to test for significance.

Data loading and prep

First we read in the Genotypes. There are not many markers here, and the reason why not is not explained in the paper… Something to ask Aaron about.

setwd("/home/beissinger/Documents/WQS_Prediction/Frequency_change/")
wqsGeno <- read.csv('../../WQS/DATA/genoWQS_randImp.csv',header=T,stringsAsFactors=F)

Now we’ll import the map.

wqsMap <- read.csv('../../WQS/DATA/wqsMap_randImp.csv',stringsAsFactors=F)

Gapit cannot work with non-integer chromosomes. Remove those labeled “0”

remMap <- which(wqsMap$Chromosome == 0)
remGeno <- remMap+1

wqsGeno<-wqsGeno[,-remGeno]
wqsMap<-wqsMap[-remMap,]

Now split individuals into different data frames according to their cycle

names(wqsGeno)[1] <- "Taxa"
CycleIndicator <- as.numeric(unlist(strsplit(wqsGeno$Taxa,split="_C"))[seq(2,2*nrow(wqsGeno),2)])

Cycle0 <- wqsGeno[which(CycleIndicator == 0),]
Cycle1 <- wqsGeno[which(CycleIndicator == 1),]
Cycle2 <- wqsGeno[which(CycleIndicator == 2),]
Cycle3 <- wqsGeno[which(CycleIndicator == 3),]
Cycle4 <- wqsGeno[which(CycleIndicator == 4),]
Cycle5 <- wqsGeno[which(CycleIndicator == 5),]
CycleList <- list(Cycle0,Cycle1,Cycle2,Cycle3,Cycle4,Cycle5)

Analysis

The next step is to calculate the allele frequency at each cycle.

frequencies<-matrix(nrow=ncol(wqsGeno)-1,ncol=6)
for(i in 1:6){
frequencies[,i] <- colMeans(CycleList[[i]][,-1],na.rm=T)/2
}
frequencies <- as.data.frame(frequencies)
names(frequencies) <- c("Cycle0","Cycle1","Cycle2","Cycle3","Cycle4","Cycle5")

Now load in effects estimates.

adf <- read.csv("../GWAS_effects/GWAS_adf/GAPIT..Intercept.BLUP.Allelic_Effect_Estimates.csv")
ndf <- read.csv("../GWAS_effects/GWAS_ndf/GAPIT..Intercept.BLUP.Allelic_Effect_Estimates.csv")
ivd <- read.csv("../GWAS_effects/GWAS_ivd/GAPIT..Intercept.BLUP.Allelic_Effect_Estimates.csv")
cp <- read.csv("../GWAS_effects/GWAS_cp/GAPIT..Intercept.BLUP.Allelic_Effect_Estimates.csv")
starch <- read.csv("../GWAS_effects/GWAS_starch/GAPIT..Intercept.BLUP.Allelic_Effect_Estimates.csv")
yield<- read.csv("../GWAS_effects/GWAS_yield/GAPIT..Intercept.BLUP.Allelic_Effect_Estimates.csv")
drymat<- read.csv("../GWAS_effects/GWAS_drymat/GAPIT..Intercept.BLUP.Allelic_Effect_Estimates.csv")

Now compute allele frequency change from cycle 2 to 5 and make a histogram

change<-frequencies$Cycle5-frequencies$Cycle2
hist(change,main=paste("Histogram of C2 to C5 Frequency Change, Mean=",round(mean(change,na.rm=T),digits=3),sep=""))

Now compute the sum of frequency*change

adf_result <- sum(change*adf$Allelic.Effect.Estimate,na.rm=T)
ndf_result <- sum(change*ndf$Allelic.Effect.Estimate,na.rm=T)
ivd_result <- sum(change*ivd$Allelic.Effect.Estimate,na.rm=T)
cp_result <- sum(change*cp$Allelic.Effect.Estimate,na.rm=T)
starch_result <- sum(change*starch$Allelic.Effect.Estimate,na.rm=T)
yield_result <- sum(change*yield$Allelic.Effect.Estimate,na.rm=T)
drymat_result <- sum(change*drymat$Allelic.Effect.Estimate,na.rm=T)

Now do a quick permutation test. Are there reason that permuting SNPs is not a valid approach? (I can’t think of any at the moment)

adf_test<-c(); ndf_test<-c(); ivd_test<-c(); cp_test<-c(); starch_test<-c(); yield_test<-c(); drymat_test<-c()
for(i in 1:1000){
  boot <- sample(change,length(change),replace=T)
  adf_test[i]<-sum(boot*adf$Allelic.Effect.Estimate,na.rm=T)
  ndf_test[i]<-sum(boot*ndf$Allelic.Effect.Estimate,na.rm=T) 
  ivd_test[i]<-sum(boot*ivd$Allelic.Effect.Estimate,na.rm=T)
  cp_test[i]<-sum(boot*cp$Allelic.Effect.Estimate,na.rm=T)
  starch_test[i]<-sum(boot*starch$Allelic.Effect.Estimate,na.rm=T)
  yield_test[i]<-sum(boot*yield$Allelic.Effect.Estimate,na.rm=T)
  drymat_test[i]<-sum(boot*drymat$Allelic.Effect.Estimate,na.rm=T)
  }

Results

Plots below show the distribution of null tests compared to the observed value. For all traits but yield, we have a significant result! Could this be right?

Now make pretty cumulative plots for each trait, like Jochen did with milk yield.

adf$Allelic.Effect.Estimate[which(is.na(adf$Allelic.Effect.Estimate))] <- 0### Remove NAs
ndf$Allelic.Effect.Estimate[which(is.na(ndf$Allelic.Effect.Estimate))] <- 0### Remove NAs
ivd$Allelic.Effect.Estimate[which(is.na(ivd$Allelic.Effect.Estimate))] <- 0### Remove NAs
cp$Allelic.Effect.Estimate[which(is.na(cp$Allelic.Effect.Estimate))] <- 0### Remove NAs
starch$Allelic.Effect.Estimate[which(is.na(starch$Allelic.Effect.Estimate))] <- 0### Remove NAs
yield$Allelic.Effect.Estimate[which(is.na(yield$Allelic.Effect.Estimate))] <- 0### Remove NAs
drymat$Allelic.Effect.Estimate[which(is.na(drymat$Allelic.Effect.Estimate))] <- 0### Remove NAs

cumulative <- data.frame(adf=rep(NA,nrow(wqsMap)),ndf=NA,ivd=NA,cp=NA,starch=NA,yield=NA,drymat=NA)
for(i in 1:nrow(cumulative)){
  if(i==1){
  cumulative$adf[i] <- change[i]*adf$Allelic.Effect.Estimate[i]
  cumulative$ndf[i] <- change[i]*ndf$Allelic.Effect.Estimate[i]
  cumulative$ivd[i] <- change[i]*ivd$Allelic.Effect.Estimate[i]
  cumulative$cp[i] <- change[i]*cp$Allelic.Effect.Estimate[i] 
  cumulative$starch[i] <- change[i]*starch$Allelic.Effect.Estimate[i]
  cumulative$yield[i] <- change[i]*yield$Allelic.Effect.Estimate[i]
  cumulative$drymat[i] <- change[i]*drymat$Allelic.Effect.Estimate[i]     
  }
  if(i>1){
  cumulative$adf[i] <- cumulative$adf[i-1]+change[i]*adf$Allelic.Effect.Estimate[i]
  cumulative$ndf[i] <- cumulative$ndf[i-1]+change[i]*ndf$Allelic.Effect.Estimate[i]
  cumulative$ivd[i] <- cumulative$ivd[i-1]+change[i]*ivd$Allelic.Effect.Estimate[i]
  cumulative$cp[i] <- cumulative$cp[i-1]+change[i]*cp$Allelic.Effect.Estimate[i] 
  cumulative$starch[i] <- cumulative$starch[i-1]+change[i]*starch$Allelic.Effect.Estimate[i]
  cumulative$yield[i] <- cumulative$yield[i-1]+change[i]*yield$Allelic.Effect.Estimate[i]
  cumulative$drymat[i] <- cumulative$drymat[i-1]+change[i]*drymat$Allelic.Effect.Estimate[i]  
  }
}
